01:32.521 --> 01:34.022
He's here.

01:37.168 --> 01:39.128
- Carl.
- Martin.

01:39.212 --> 01:40.588
Mr. Hale,
it's an honor.

01:40.671 --> 01:42.882
When I was a kid, I saved
that Time magazine cover,

01:43.049 --> 01:44.967
"The Man Who Built New York."

01:45.051 --> 01:46.402
You're the reason I got
into this business.

01:46.427 --> 01:47.637
Sit, please.

01:47.720 --> 01:51.724
And congratulations on
the downtown contract.

01:53.184 --> 01:55.561
Thank you. I didn't know
the word was out yet.

01:55.645 --> 01:58.940
Hard to keep the word in on a
$200 million deal like that.

01:59.899 --> 02:02.026
I hear you lobbied
Councilman Clark pretty hard.

02:02.568 --> 02:04.111
Just a few steak dinners,
that's all.

02:04.237 --> 02:05.822
I'm not talking about the Kobe.

02:07.240 --> 02:10.493
- Look, Martin...
- You called the Hale Group a "relic."

02:10.576 --> 02:12.703
I'm not sure if those
were my exact words.

02:12.787 --> 02:17.583
No. Your exact words were, "The old
man won't be around for long."

02:18.376 --> 02:21.254
At least, that's how
the Councilman remembers it.

02:24.048 --> 02:26.803
- You're getting the contract, aren't you?
- I don't want the contract.

02:26.926 --> 02:29.512
You think $200 million
means you've arrived?

02:29.595 --> 02:33.724
What I want is to offer you
a lesson from an "old man,"

02:34.892 --> 02:36.098
free of charge.

02:36.102 --> 02:38.271
We've spoken with
Simon and Cohen.

02:38.396 --> 02:41.607
Between them, they control
seven seats on your board.

02:41.774 --> 02:43.067
And they support me.

02:43.150 --> 02:47.572
They've come to see the need for
someone with the wisdom of experience.

02:47.655 --> 02:49.532
And someone who might remember

02:49.615 --> 02:52.660
that Councilman Clark's first
campaign, 30 years ago,

02:52.785 --> 02:54.537
was bankrolled by
Mr. Hale here.

02:54.620 --> 02:59.250
Try and appreciate
the irony, Mr. Baldwin.

03:01.752 --> 03:04.213
You say I'm the reason
you got into this business?

03:05.673 --> 03:07.967
Now, I'm the reason you're out.

03:11.304 --> 03:12.471
You son of a bitch!

03:12.805 --> 03:15.086
You're gonna be dead in a year.
And then who gives a shit?

03:20.813 --> 03:22.148
He's wrong.

03:24.859 --> 03:26.652
I won't last six months.

03:27.028 --> 03:30.364
It's metastasized.
Liver and lungs.

03:30.865 --> 03:33.826
This morning the oncologist was
talking about hospice care.

03:34.952 --> 03:37.163
- I'm sorry.
- Don't be.

03:38.956 --> 03:40.291
What you and
Judith went through,

03:40.374 --> 03:43.419
losing a child,
that's a tragedy.

03:44.295 --> 03:48.007
An old man dying. I'm supposed
to say, "That's life."

03:49.508 --> 03:51.677
Still feels like
a kick in the nuts.

03:52.386 --> 03:53.679
Have you told Claire?

03:53.763 --> 03:55.097
I haven't had a chance.

03:55.181 --> 03:57.558
Well, she won't return my calls.

03:58.434 --> 04:00.519
Jesus, Damian,
if she only knew...

04:00.645 --> 04:02.688
She has every
reason to be angry.

04:03.564 --> 04:05.399
Oh, peanuts.

04:05.483 --> 04:06.901
I'll send...
I'll send it back.

04:06.984 --> 04:09.862
Cancer's eating me alive, and
I'm worried about allergies.

04:11.656 --> 04:13.408
Maybe I should order a P...

04:14.158 --> 04:15.308
PB&J.

04:17.577 --> 04:18.728
No.

04:24.001 --> 04:26.295
You know, I wanted
to tear all this down

04:26.420 --> 04:28.714
in the '70s,
replace it with condos.

04:29.006 --> 04:31.258
- And now?
- Couldn't if I tried.

04:31.384 --> 04:33.636
Mayor declared it a landmark.

04:37.556 --> 04:41.060
Oh, Martin, you ever hear about
something called "shedding"?

04:41.602 --> 04:44.021
Shedding?
You mean like a snake?

04:44.647 --> 04:46.321
Ah, it's nothing.
Forget about it.

04:46.625 --> 04:48.350
It's just something
I was reading about.

05:08.963 --> 05:11.924
<i>Hi. You've reached Claire.
Please leave a message.</i>

05:29.108 --> 05:32.069
How many? Before me?

05:32.445 --> 05:33.779
Less than a dozen.

05:34.572 --> 05:36.574
Shedding is an
exclusive endeavor.

05:36.657 --> 05:38.617
You mean expensive,
Dr. Albright.

05:38.993 --> 05:41.829
Well, all of our clients are wealthy,
but that's not how they're chosen.

05:41.912 --> 05:44.248
No, we cater to the great.

05:44.790 --> 05:47.668
The visionaries, whose loss
would be a blow to all of us.

05:47.752 --> 05:50.087
Simply put, we offer
humanity's greatest minds

05:50.171 --> 05:52.506
more time to
fulfill their potential.

05:53.257 --> 05:58.429
If you think about it, your
homes, your yacht, your jet...

05:58.512 --> 06:01.098
All custom-built by the
world's finest craftsmen.

06:01.182 --> 06:03.184
And so will your
new body be as well.

06:04.935 --> 06:06.604
Genetically engineered
for perfection.

06:06.687 --> 06:09.065
Harvested to maturity,
so looks, athleticism,

06:09.148 --> 06:11.400
every detail of your new anatomy

06:11.484 --> 06:14.779
will be designed to offer you the
very best of the human experience.

06:17.990 --> 06:20.534
- A reflex.
- It's alive?

06:20.659 --> 06:22.036
Only in the most basic sense.

06:22.119 --> 06:27.875
A bundle of organic tissue.
But right now an empty vessel.

06:29.502 --> 06:33.715
If you can really do what you
say, then why the makeshift lab?

06:33.839 --> 06:35.925
I mean, why all the secrecy?

06:39.845 --> 06:41.680
You're asking
the wrong question.

06:41.847 --> 06:45.017
Oh. What's
the right question?

06:48.437 --> 06:51.524
You've built
an empire from the ground up.

06:52.191 --> 06:57.571
Worked every day to create
something from nothing.

06:59.031 --> 07:02.701
Now, as you slip away,

07:05.371 --> 07:08.707
people will call
your work your "legacy."

07:10.960 --> 07:14.630
They'll insist that your buildings
somehow make you immortal.

07:15.047 --> 07:16.215
What's your point?

07:17.049 --> 07:19.093
Do you feel immortal?

07:39.822 --> 07:41.582
Thanks for
supporting the cause, guys.

07:41.907 --> 07:43.547
I'm gonna give
him a call, but...

07:43.659 --> 07:45.219
Yeah,
that's what I was thinking.

07:46.245 --> 07:47.580
Here,
sir, would you like a flyer?

07:47.746 --> 07:50.416
Remember, we want everyone
at the rally to be respectful.

07:51.095 --> 07:53.169
We're trying to win people over.

07:55.963 --> 07:57.113
Dad.

08:01.093 --> 08:03.079
Aren't you gonna introduce me?

08:03.971 --> 08:05.723
I'm sorry to show up like this.

08:05.848 --> 08:07.568
It's the only place I
knew I could find you.

08:07.641 --> 08:08.809
Well, I'm kind of in
the middle of something.

08:08.893 --> 08:11.437
Let's take a ride uptown
to that place by Macy's.

08:11.520 --> 08:15.024
- You used to love their sundaes.
- Yeah, when I was eight.

08:20.613 --> 08:22.356
Is something wrong?

08:23.449 --> 08:25.643
- You don't look well.
- I'm fine.

08:26.035 --> 08:28.746
Now, please take a ride with me.

08:28.829 --> 08:31.081
Look, it's just
a bad time, okay?

08:31.165 --> 08:33.292
- Maybe we can meet up later.
- Not later.

08:34.126 --> 08:37.462
- The revolution can wait, Claire.
- I don't get you.

08:37.962 --> 08:40.131
Months go by.
Years even.

08:40.633 --> 08:42.301
I'm at work, Dad.

08:42.801 --> 08:46.430
This isn't work. It's a bunch
of children throwing a tantrum.

08:54.313 --> 08:56.523
Look, I didn't come
here to do this again.

08:57.900 --> 09:00.903
- I came because I want to make things right.
- What does that mean?

09:00.986 --> 09:02.238
I know you're short on funds.

09:02.621 --> 09:03.906
- How...
- Just take it.

09:03.989 --> 09:05.989
You know, you can really be
a manipulative asshole.

09:06.992 --> 09:09.078
Don't be a fool, Claire.
I'm trying, here.

09:09.161 --> 09:10.913
No, you're not. You're
doing what you always do.

09:10.996 --> 09:14.792
Showing up on your terms, expecting
your checkbook to solve everything.

09:36.605 --> 09:38.774
<i>I am talking about a future</i>

09:38.857 --> 09:42.444
<i>where the aged and infirm
can shed their prisons.</i>

09:44.780 --> 09:46.031
<i>A future where...</i>

09:47.741 --> 09:49.535
<i>Where the fate of a healthy mind</i>

09:50.536 --> 09:52.621
<i>is not determined by the fate</i>

09:52.705 --> 09:53.855
<i>of a failing body.</i>

09:57.793 --> 09:58.943
Okay...

10:00.004 --> 10:02.464
Oh, my goodness.

10:26.447 --> 10:27.781
Albright.

10:28.657 --> 10:33.746
I don't feel immortal.

10:34.997 --> 10:39.084
If we do this, there's no turning back.
Your old life is over.

10:39.752 --> 10:42.004
You see someone from your
past, you walk away.

10:42.087 --> 10:43.589
Is that clear, Mr. Hale?

10:43.672 --> 10:46.175
You have your conditions,
I have mine.

10:46.258 --> 10:48.218
You get paid
after the procedure.

10:48.344 --> 10:50.304
I may be dying,
but I'm not a fool.

10:51.430 --> 10:54.433
Settle your affairs and fly
to New Orleans on Tuesday.

10:55.601 --> 10:58.520
Your death needs to
be public, Mr. Hale.

10:58.604 --> 11:03.233
Have lunch at Commander's. I
recommend the chicory coffee.

11:06.862 --> 11:09.281
You've reached the
residence of Martin and Judy.

11:09.365 --> 11:11.367
Please leave a message.

11:11.950 --> 11:14.453
Sorry to bother you
at the ranch, Martin.

11:15.537 --> 11:19.458
You mind meeting me for lunch
in New Orleans?

11:37.976 --> 11:39.395
<i>Yeah,
it's a three-point favorite,</i>

11:39.478 --> 11:41.563
<i>and that just means a home field
advantage for New Orleans.</i>

11:41.647 --> 11:43.727
<i>Well, you know, we've seen
this before, when these...</i>

12:08.507 --> 12:11.718
Are you going to stay?
George wants you to.

12:13.345 --> 12:16.265
The Hale Group without Hale? No.

12:16.849 --> 12:17.999
Thank you.

12:19.685 --> 12:23.230
Judy's been spending most of her
time up the coast at the ranch.

12:29.862 --> 12:34.366
I think it's time for me to cash
out and join her full-time.

12:39.705 --> 12:42.875
I wish you could
drive out, come see the new place.

12:43.542 --> 12:45.377
If the maids
would ever stop quitting,

12:45.461 --> 12:47.921
we might finally be
ready for visitors.

12:50.924 --> 12:52.074
Damian, are you okay?

12:57.055 --> 12:58.205
What's the matter?

12:58.974 --> 13:00.350
- I...
- What?

13:00.434 --> 13:01.584
What?

13:02.728 --> 13:04.146
Call 911!

13:04.605 --> 13:06.356
Damian!

13:06.940 --> 13:08.901
Damian!
Do you have your EpiPen?

13:09.067 --> 13:10.944
<i>Do you have it with you?
He can't breathe!</i>

13:17.618 --> 13:18.619
ETA five minutes.

13:18.702 --> 13:21.580
Mr. Hale? Mr. Hale?

13:21.663 --> 13:25.501
The good news is you're not
going into anaphylactic shock.

13:25.584 --> 13:27.669
You just feel like you are.

13:28.754 --> 13:32.341
The bad news is
your body needs to arrive DOA

13:32.424 --> 13:34.426
at Tulane Hospital
in about 20 minutes.

13:45.354 --> 13:47.564
Open your mouth, please.

13:47.648 --> 13:49.648
Have all your fillings been removed?
